\par }\pard \ql \fi-600\li600\ri0\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\tx542\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid7558447 {\f0\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033\insrsid7558447\charrsid7018359 I:\tab Can you tell me the house where you were born?

\par WF:\tab I was born in Lichborough Rectory, in Northamptonshire.
\par I:\tab That was 1892?
\par WF:\tab 1889.
\par I:\tab How many years did you live there?
\par WF:\tab We lived there about - five years.
\par I:\tab And then where did you go to?
\par WF:\tab Then we went to Norfolk Island. The whole family went to Norfolk Island. And my father - he went off to the Solomon Islands. In the - mission ship the Southern Cross. And he -
\par I:\tab How long were you abroad?
\par WF:\tab We were abroad then in my childhood seven years.
\par I:\tab When you came back where did you come back to?
\par WF:\tab We back to - stay at first at Windsor, with my grandmother and then went to Lichborough, Northamptonshire.
\par I:\tab Back again to the rectory?
\par WF:\tab Yes. And then - my father got a place in - Waltham St Laurence in Berkshire. He was assistant curate there - and that little church to look after.
\par I:\tab How old was your father when you were born, do you remember?
\par WF:\tab I think he was thirty-four. Yes.
\par I:\tab Where did he come from?
\par WF:\tab He came from Stoke Mandeville. A place by here, yes.
\par I:\tab How old was your mother when you were born?
\par WF:\tab She was - twenty-seven. Yes.
\par I:\tab Where did she come from?
\par WF:\tab She came from - Worcestershire. That was her home. Near Birmingham.
\par I:\tab And you thought her people were in industry?
\par WF:\tab I thought - they were, but I never heard much about it but - her father and mother had a - huge sort of - estate, a lot of - animals and - lot of servants, they're very rich I think. Mm.
\par I:\tab Can you describe to me the house where you were born and lived for five years?
\par WF:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How big was it, how many rooms did it have?
\par WF:\tab The - it had twenty-one rooms as far as I remember. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did it look like?
\par WF:\tab A big - you know, like a big - I don't know what it looked like.
\par I:\tab What were those rooms, can you tell me?
\par WF:\tab There was - the - lavatory, then there was the - study. Little room facing south. Then there was the - dining room, big - high room, facing south. And then the drawing room. And - then - store cupboard. Then a ki
tchen. Then a scullery. And then - up the other way, coming from - north to south there was - I think that was all, yes. Then upstairs there was -
\par I:\tab Did the staff have a sitting room at all?
\par WF:\tab No, no.
\par I:\tab They where in the kitchen?
\par WF:\tab No, they just rele
gated to the kitchen. And lived up in the attics. And - the bedrooms were - east to west - there's one bedroom for - us boys when we stayed there later, there's - father's and mother's room. Big bedroom. Then there's a spare bedroom. They'd all got single
 beds as far as I remember or nearly - all then there were - two or three small bedrooms. One was converted into a bathroom. That was all I can remember I think.
\par I:\tab And then attics upstairs?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Top floor, there were several rooms up there. Three attics I remember, quite a - quite big rooms, and children - used to play in them. Mm.
\par I:\tab You just had one brother didn't you?
\par WF:\tab Yes, just one brother.
\par I:\tab Do you know if your mother ever did any work before she married?
\par WF:\tab I shouldn't - well - her mother died when she was only eleven, and - she was dissipated among - relations, and she spent - I think most of her time with her - her crusty old grandmother. But -
\par I:\tab How did she meet your father, do you know?
\par WF:\tab She first met him - when she was jumping across Brackley bridge, Brackley - stream I mean. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did he catch her?
\par WF:\tab Just down - close by here, he saw her there and said - who's is that girl jumping that stream? They said - that's one of the Phelpston's, that was her family. And - but - she - she wa
s then living at Westbury, not far from here. That's the first time. Then he didn't see her again 'til - she was - living - at that time at Wheatley near Oxford. And he went - take the services there. And - her three sisters there, and he - and he - chose
 her you see as the best looking. As she certainly was. And - then they got married in 1887, then took this family living Lichborough.
\par I:\tab It was in your father's family?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did he take it over from your grandfather?
\par WF:\tab Yes. He took it over from grandfather, who - bought the living I think, or had it somehow from - Lady Knightly Forsley - not far from here either, near Preston Capes it is.
\par I:\tab Another big house was it?
\par WF:\tab No. Which house?
\par I:\tab The Lichborough?
\par WF:\tab Oh that was - yes, that was the biggest house, yes, that's the twenty-one-roomed house. Counting all sorts of little - odds and ends of rooms that is I can't remember each one but I did count them but -
\par I:\tab What sort of staff did you have, can you remember?
\par WF:\tab Oh I can't tell, there was - there was always a gardener there and a gardener's boy, and - there was a - an indoor girl - maid, called the twenty whatever that was. And -
\par I:\tab Cook did you have?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we had a cook I think,
\par I:\tab Did you have a nursemaid?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we had a - girl, village girl called Jenny West - for a nursemaid, But when we - departed and went out to Norfolk Island - they found a girl from - had lost her parents or been - separated from them I think, and she came out with us.
\par I:\tab How old was she?
\par WF:\tab She was - she died at the age of ninety-seven about - two years ago. I think she was about - eighteen or so when she came with us.
\par I:\tab Did you like her?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we - yes, yes, we liked her very much. Yes.
\par I:\tab Can you remember the domestic routine in your time at Lichborough, did you have anybody else staying in the house, any relatives?
\par WF:\tab I - can't remember much, I was only three - under three when I left. I can't remember anybody staying in the house. I can hardly remember - anyone about the place at all. Except in a very dim way.
\par I:\tab Do you remember the upping and going?
\par WF:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Do you remember the actual move?
\par WF:\tab No, I don't, no. No, I don't. Didn't seem to leave any impression on me I remembered - very silly little - incidents.
\par I:\tab Can you tell me some?
\par WF:\tab Such as - looking out and seeing the snow in one of the cold winters of the early 1890's, and seeing squirrels running about. Hearing wolves and that sort of thing, I can't remember anything at all important.
\par I:\tab Little incidents are important?
\par WF:\tab I suppose they seem important, yes.
\par I:\tab They're quite important to us too,
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Can you remember much - of the time abroad?
\par WF:\tab I can remember all that, yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of schooling did you have?
\par WF:\tab 
Oh we - at home - we had a little bit of schooling, then there's a - mission they had a New Zealander, called Miss Farr - who used to - take us, run a little school there, only about - three or four - white children in the place, oh yes, sometimes - do su
ms or something of that sort of thing with the - black people and - and -
\par I:\tab Did you play with them?
\par WF:\tab Oh rather, yes, I think so.
\par I:\tab You weren't kept apart?
\par WF:\tab No. No, went all over the place with them. Ran races with them, they always won though. Mm.
\par I:\tab What sort of life was it there?
\par WF:\tab Oh it's a lovely life there.
\par I:\tab Was there any luxury about it, did you live grandly?
\par WF:\tab No, didn't have any - no luxuries. No. Horrible - meals - in the middle of the day. Yes. Just meat and -, sweet potatoes, I belie
ve we have them in England now. And - most of our meals were out on the veranda which was nice. In the open air. Used to drink a lot of milk, it was a thin - took a - about four big mugfulls to - to nourish one. Mm. And sometimes had cold meat - in the ev
ening.
\par I:\tab Was your mother happy there?
\par WF:\tab Oh she was very happy, yes. Oh goodness yes.
\par I:\tab Did she have to work to help your father?
\par WF:\tab I don't think so. No, we had a half dozen girls in the house. Native girls. And - we were great friends with them.
\par I:\tab Did your father like it?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes. Yes. It was - there's a lot of separation at - had to go off for eight months in the year - to be a missionary in the -
\par I:\tab Was that going into the darkest bits?
\par WF:\tab Into the - into the isle - heathen islands.
\par I:\tab You weren't taken along?
\par WF:\tab No, no, no.
\par I:\tab Was it thought to be dangerous?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes. Yes, they wouldn't take a child there. But the - Presbyterian missionaries had children out in those parts - in - slightly cooler parts - New Hebrides, Southern Islands, yes. Bu
t - and no ladies were supposed to go there at all. And - one missionary married - a local Norfolk Island lady, Miss Rossiter, English in race, and - she died as soon as she got there, with -
\par I:\tab A disease of something?
\par WF:\tab No - the - silly people they started having a family, and - on their - being rocked about on the ship - that woman get a child - get - that she -
\par I:\tab I suppose there were no medical facilities?
\par WF:\tab Yes, he was a doctor, so - yes. So he -
\par I:\tab But he couldn't save her?
\par WF:\tab He couldn't s
ave her life. It - the - the child killed her, poor thing, she was buried out there, and - then of course after that they said, well for some time they said well - that's evidence that no lady can - and a married lady - well they wouldn't have any women a
t all out there - for a few years. Then - the Bishop got married, but he didn't attempt to take his wife - into the - heathen parts. Mm.
\par I:\tab What sort of heathen were they, they weren't head-hunters were they?
\par WF:\tab They were head-hunters, yes, and cannibals, yes, oh yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father tell stories of them when he came back?
\par WF:\tab Yes, yes, father wasn't in quite such a - bad place, it was - supposed to be main - mainly Christian where - father was. But - they were raided sometimes, I think by - head hunters
. It was - a game they had - to get as many heads as they could and hang them up in their huts, yes.
\par I:\tab Was your mother worried about him?
\par WF:\tab Oh well yes, a little bit I suppose. Very very thankful when he came - came back. They - used to wonder whether -
 whether we'd see him again each time he went. Mm. That was very - rough then. They knew nothing about medicine, medical things, and what's the cause of malarial fever, they didn't know that. But they knew that quinine should be used for it. But that's ab
out all.
\par I:\tab Did you get ill, your family at all?
\par WF:\tab Oh no, we didn't get ill, no. Don't think so, just had measles once but - no, we didn't get - really ill. And - it was primitive, a primitive sort of life, we ran about barefooted. Got - bad feet, stone b
ruises, they call them. But we didn't get to be ill.
\par I:\tab When you came back which year was that?
\par WF:\tab That was 1899. March.
\par I:\tab Do you remember the coming back?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I remember that, yes.
\par I:\tab Can you tell me about it?
\par WF:\tab Mm. We had a dreadful - well we were - whisked off in the early morning so we couldn't see all the weeping - native girls all round, must have - been a - a tragic affair.
\par I:\tab They were sad to see you go were they?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, they were sad indeed.
\par I:\tab Was it the end of your father's term there?
\par WF:\tab 'Twas the end of his term, he had to stay seven years at a time. That was the end of - one - period, and he - went home expecting to go back again. And -
\par I:\tab So you left in the early morning?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes. Before anyone was up. And drove away in the two - morning twilight.
\par I:\tab Were you sad or excited?
\par WF:\tab Frightfully sad. Mm hm. Yes.
\par I:\tab How about your mother?
\par WF:\tab Oh she was sad too, she hoped to come back. But they loved the place there, people. And they - she had plenty to do there. Had these six gir
ls to look after and - and - bandage them and wash their sores, which they keep getting all the time. I think we all did.
\par I:\tab It must have taken quite a long time to come back?
\par WF:\tab 
Yes. Well - it's all by sea of course, by - three months I think usually. Yes. It was about - I think about forty-two days, that's about six weeks isn't it, from Melbourne - Australia, they had to get to Melbourne - first. Got a - we got a ship at Sidney,
 three thousand tons she was. Half sailing and half steam.
\par I:\tab Did you like the journey?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Oh yes. Yes, it was - lovely - a nice journey, I think we soon forgot all - our regrets. Yes. I think so.
\par I:\tab What were your feelings when you arrived, do you remember?
\par WF:\tab Well -
\par I:\tab Did it seem strange to you, the life?
\par WF:\tab Happy for a time, certainly. Yes, it all seemed strange in England. Seemed awful big - going to school at first - and English children seemed very strange things indeed, didn't like them at al
l. No. Oh I daresay I liked some of them, but I didn't like being at school much. Well we had had - all on our own the time we were - we were out there.
\par I:\tab And a lot of freedom?
\par WF:\tab Lot of freedom, yes, we'd had freedom and - they were rather worshipped and looked to 'cos here we're just - knocked about. And - yes.
\par I:\tab When you settled down again and your father got the assistant curate you said didn't you?
\par WF:\tab Yes, he - was an assistant at - Waltham St Lawrence in Berkshire. We liked that place very much. Had a year there. Then he - went to Bromhall outside Bedford. Stayed there for twenty-five years. Mm.
\par I:\tab That would be the place you lived at most of the time?
\par WF:\tab Longest time was Bromwell near Bedford.
\par I:\tab Did you again have staff in the house?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we - had about - two maids usually, in the house, and the gardener in the garden.
\par I:\tab Did your mother do any work in the house?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, she - well a lot of supervising the maids I suppose but - she used to do the cooking herself - I think. It was mainly looking after - the girls, her housework was. Girls about - thirteen or fourteen, fifteen or so. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they come in from the village?
\par WF:\tab They came in from - from - my birthplace, most of them at first, Northamptonshire, yes.
\par I:\tab And they lived in?
\par WF:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab All of them?
\par WF:\tab Then afterwards - after a year or two it began - getting - to know the village girls and they came. At one stage - think it was eleven years. Yes, they stayed quite a long time, most of - or more. They used to get very faithful. Yes.
\par I:\tab Was yours a happy household?
\par WF:\tab Yes, oh yes, was - a very - very happy.
\par I:\tab Your mother and father got on well together did they?
\par WF:\tab My goodness yes. Mm.
\par I:\tab Did father help at all in the house?
\par WF:\tab No. He couldn't - he couldn't do anything, no.
\par I:\tab He was there of course most of the time?
\par WF:\tab Yes, yes, there but - I never saw him helping in the house.
\par I:\tab Did you boys help in the house at all?
\par WF:\tab No, well they wouldn't let us. We started clearing the table, they said, that's not your job. And we wanted to help sometimes but - we weren't encouraged to.
\par I:\tab Which school did you go to?
\par WF:\tab Went to - St Briglodge in Kent first.
\par I:\tab This was away at school?
\par WF:\tab Yes, to prep school. And -
\par I:\tab Did you ever attend a day school when you came back?
\par WF:\tab No. No, no, not that, no. Then I went to St Edwards School, Oxford, and - where another - Norfolk Island - white boy had been. Yes. And that's the only school I know.
\par I:\tab When you were at home was the discipline fairly strict, did you have to go to bed at certain times, and meal times?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes, we - got up at seven - half past seven. Yes.
\par I:\tab In bed at what time?
\par WF:\tab Bed at - oh nine I should think. Half past eight was it. Half past eight I seem to think, yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have help in going to bed or did you put yourselves to bed, you boys.
\par WF:\tab In England we put ourselves to bed.
\par I:\tab But abroad you'd had help?
\par WF:\tab Yes. We were bathed every night and - and - put to bed. Oh yes, we had - had a nursemaid do this there. Mother used to bath us and - tuck us up.
\par I:\tab Mother looked after you quite a lot did she?
\par WF:\tab Yes, yes she did.
\par I:\tab She didn't leave you to the nursemaid?
\par WF:\tab No, not such a great deal. Looked after my - younger brother more than - myself, I was always - pretty much on my own. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were you independent sort of person?
\par WF:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you share a bedroom with your brother?
\par WF:\tab No, no. I had a bedroom of m
y own. And - wretched girls - all night they were learning their collects for next Sunday. And instead of saying - saying them all together they were - they were all saying different parts at the same time, learn - learning different bits, and - they spen
t the rest of the time singing endless psalms, hymns, psalms, anything they could think of.
\par I:\tab These were the native girls were they?
\par WF:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab They liked doing that did they?
\par WF:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Or did they have to do it?
\par WF:\tab Oh they liked doing that. They would
n't be quiet 'til about eleven. Well I don't know when it was, it was - it kept me awake. I - rebelled against it but - I was told I had to put up with it. The rats would come out and run around the room that I was all alone with.
\par I:\tab Rats?
\par WF:\tab Yes. It was awful. That part was the worst. And that seemed like a long dark tunnel. My brother slept with the parents all the time. Mm. In their room.
\par I:\tab Did you tell your parents you were frightened?
\par WF:\tab No, I don't think so, but I told them I - didn't like the girls singing. Their singing wasn't very musical - so it was - not very beautiful.
\par I:\tab You were expected to be a bit tough were you?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Mm.
\par I:\tab It was quite strange for a little boy?
\par WF:\tab - Yes, it was,
\par I:\tab Did you have a bathroom there?
\par WF:\tab Oh - no, there wasn't a bathroom, had a - had a bath in the bedroom. Yes.
\par I:\tab When you were back in England by then there were bathrooms in the big houses?
\par WF:\tab Yes - the - primitive sort of things when we first arrived in England.
\par I:\tab What was that?
\par WF:\tab Well it was - one of
 those tin things, the - they used to have - they used to wear end and get rust didn't we, they put a - quite a nice bath into the room, and - divided it off so that other people could come in - when they wanted a bath. It was in our bedroom, we had the -
 hot water cistern in the bedroom. And we were awfully grateful for that. Always had a warm room. Never went to bed with cold feet.
\par I:\tab Can we talk a bit about mealtimes this is now back in England?
\par WF:\tab Mm. Mm.
\par I:\tab Where did you have - where did the family eat their meals?
\par WF:\tab Eat their meals in the dining room. Yes.
\par I:\tab Always?
\par WF:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab You presumably had tea in the drawing room would you?
\par WF:\tab Well not every not often.
\par I:\tab Where would tea be had?
\par WF:\tab In the - in the dining room. Usually, yes.
\par I:\tab Did you and your brother have meals at the same time as your parents?
\par WF:\tab In - in England I think we did. Yes. Not at Norfolk Island. When we were - when I was about - ten or so we began having - yes, had all the meals together. Breakfast half past eight, lunch at
 one. Tea at four thirty and supper at seven thirty. It was quite regular because we - had the maid to do things, and the cook.
\par I:\tab What sort of things did you have for breakfast?
\par WF:\tab Oh always porridge, it was - heated up on the stove all night. And - oh t
he ordinary things. Fish or - bacon or anything of that sort. Then father became vegetarian. When I was about sixteen. And mother wouldn't - change over but we two boys would. So we never had any meat after that at home. Not much anywhere else for that ma
tter, no.
\par I:\tab But mother wouldn't change?
\par WF:\tab Mother wouldn't change, no. But then - we lost her you see, she - she got typhoid fever and was - called home. Yes. We were only in England about seven years and then she was - she left us. Mm, it was sad because
 we - I suppose if - father and mother had gone back - to their work - at the other side of the world, missionary work, I suppose she wouldn't have got typhoid fever, 'cos I don't think there was any - strange to say. Yes. I - I never heard of any - not s
ure, there may have been some but I didn't hear - never heard of any on Norfolk Island where we lived. Presumably she wouldn't have got it. There were no drains and that.
\par I:\tab Going back to eating and drinking, what did you have to drink in your family at meals?
\par WF:\tab Oh, just -
\par I:\tab What did you have to drink at breakfast time?
\par WF:\tab Oh we just had coffee at breakfast and - water at - dinner, and then these cups of tea.
\par I:\tab And supper?
\par WF:\tab Supper we had cocoa, that was the rule.
\par I:\tab Did you have wine?
\par WF:\tab No, never h
ad wine, no. There was a Band of Hope and their temperance society and teetotal. We were all teetotallers and we - everybody was - keen on teetotalism, at least - ninety percent of the village - of the men were drunk - every Saturday night and so we - we 
practically had to set an example - to them, so we all - were expected to sign the pledge which we all did. So I always kept it 'til I went out to France in the war. Mm.
\par I:\tab France was too much for you?
\par WF:\tab They - they couldn't - well you couldn't explain to them, they thought you were being - uncooperative, disagreeable, if you didn't have their - vin blanc.
\par I:\tab The water wasn't much good either was it?
\par WF:\tab No, the water wasn't much good.
\par I:\tab Did mother do any baking things like bread and making jam?
\par WF:\tab They did at Norfolk Island, we baked bread.
\par I:\tab How about behaviour, were you expected to behave well?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we were expected to behave.
\par I:\tab I suppose being in a ministers household you were expected to set an example in all ways?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes, you were, 
yes. And there was - no staying away from church on Sunday. And - the place was locked up and the key put under the mat and - everybody went, as a matter of course, all the services. Which isn't the way now, I don't find - in this country now that's possi
ble - at all.
\par I:\tab Was your father very much the head of the family, did what he say go?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes, he was. Yes, we he kept us in order. And so did - so did the nurse - the nursemaid, she used to spank us and - order us about.
\par I:\tab How about mother, did she have to do what father said?
\par WF:\tab More or less I think. Yes, I think she did. Don't run, he got rather cross if she didn't - come up to his expectations you know.
\par I:\tab Did he have high standards?
\par WF:\tab Yes, yes, they did, yes. Yes. I remember he was quite - quite - gave her quite a lecture one day when - she didn't come to communion and he thought - she should have. Mm.
\par I:\tab Did you ever wish you weren't a minister's son?
\par WF:\tab Oh no, I don't - don't think so. No. No. The other - parents, they didn't seem as - 
nearly as good as ours. No, but - I didn't like the look of any of the other - parents who came up to - school to see their boys. No, dreadful looking - people. No, I don't - wouldn't have changed for anyone.
\par I:\tab Do you remember mealtime discipline, were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes. Yes. Yes, at school we - there's - boys used to bring in - book to look - look at, and read, they didn't talk very much. The masters all sat at the - high table. But - oh yes, at home we - we used to talk, mother
 believed in - lively conversation. Then mother - though mother, she was taken at - 1908, the angels came for her, and - and - father had about twenty-two years - on his own and that. My brother and I - my brother went out to Canada. A year after mother w
as taken, and - then soon after that I - I had - I went to a parish in the North of England. Must have been a frightfully lonely time for father. Mm. All those twenty-two years.
\par I:\tab Do you remember when you were quite small at home your attitude to the servant people in your house, were they kept very much apart?
\par WF:\tab Apart, yes, they stayed apart, we didn't -
\par I:\tab When they ate their meals?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes, they did, yes. Yes, we never - had any - mixing up - that way. Don't think it's very convenient really, that - is the chief reason - I think, don't think they're so awfully snobbish that - some people think they were.
\par I:\tab It's just a way of life isn't it?
\par WF:\tab Yes. It was a way of life which everybody carried out, yes, they mostly -
\par I:\tab And they cared for your parents didn't they?
\par WF:\tab Yes. They must have stayed round the kitchen, and - they slept - and they slept up in the attics but then we - got more liberal ideas after a while. Then they - used any spare bedrooms that were - upstairs.
\par I:\tab Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par WF:\tab Oh very yes. Charming person, yes.
\par I:\tab Did she show her affection to you?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes.
\par I:\tab She was an affectionate person?
\par WF:\tab Yes, oh very.
\par I:\tab If you had worries would you go to her with them?
\par WF:\tab Oh goodness, yes, yes.
\par I:\tab Or to your father?
\par WF:\tab Yes. No, to both. Yes.
\par I:\tab Father was easy to get on with too?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they expect you to behave in a certain way towards them?
\par WF:\tab Yes - when wri - writing you always to put - dearest - my dearest - father and mother. Mother mustn't come first like she does now. Mm.
\par I:\tab What do you call them at home?
\par WF:\tab Father - always called father and father and - called mother all sorts of things. Metier, which is Greek, and all sorts of funny things. We were more familiar with her of course.
\par I:\tab She sounds a very nice person?
\par WF:\tab Yes, she was.
\par I:\tab Did you quarrel with your brother?
\par WF:\tab Only - only just occasionally, yes. He threw a stone at me once, hit me on the leg. So I -
\par I:\tab Did your parents encourage you to be nice to each other?
\par WF:\tab Yes, suppose so. And so did the native girls at - Norfolk Island. Made us kiss each other.
\par I:\tab What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par WF:\tab Well - I went - carried on father's work as - missionary.
\par I:\tab Did they want you to be?
\par WF:\tab Yes, and I wrote to mother and she - said how delighted she was to hear that I was going out to carry on father's work, and - then very soon after that she - was - went into paradise, was called home, and I was - able to - tell her what I was go
ing to do.
\par I:\tab Did you in your household do you think more of a kind of moral upbringing than the average child?
\par WF:\tab Oh, yes, I should think so, I - yes, father was very very - emphatic - yes, his -
\par I:\tab What about things like swearing and being rude to people?
\par WF:\tab Oh we - oh he couldn't do - he couldn't - they were down on anything of that sort.
\par I:\tab Were you punished?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Oh yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of punishment did you have?
\par WF:\tab Oh had a whacking sometimes.
\par I:\tab Who administered the whacking?
\par WF:\tab Father.
\par I:\tab Did he use a strap or just his hand?
\par WF:\tab No. Birch rod. Bare skin. Yes.
\par I:\tab Was that often?
\par WF:\tab No, I only remember it once.
\par I:\tab What had you done that once?
\par WF:\tab I don't know.
\par I:\tab What sort of things did you get punished for?
\par WF:\tab I don't know really. Perhaps telling lies I expect. You know, such as that. In school we used to get - whackings and punishments, I didn't - didn't always know what they were for.
\par I:\tab Did you resent them?
\par WF:\tab Sometimes. Not - not particularly. Certainly punished at least once for something someone else had done.
\par I:\tab Would you say that looking back you learned more from your father or from your mother about how to behave toward other people?
\par WF:\tab Oh - oh
\par I:\tab Do you think mother was more of an influence?
\par WF:\tab Mother - mother I think, yes. Yes, and - certainly in the early days. Yes she was a wonderful person.
\par I:\tab And you saw more of her of course?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes, well we - yes, father was away eight months of the year you see.
\par I:\tab Whereabouts in Kent was this?
\par WF:\tab That was - between Hithe and - Sandgate.
\par I:\tab How old were you when you went there?
\par WF:\tab I was - nine when I went there. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember discussions about it at home before you went?
\par WF:\tab Before I went, no, I - I don't think so, no because my uncle was - in charge of it. Yes. Yes, it was his school.
\par I:\tab Did he own it or was he the headmaster?
\par WF:\tab Well, he was - he came from - Stoke Mandeville school. And - married my - aunt, my father's sist
er. And then when Stoke Mandeville school disbanded, he went down to - Hampshire - to - Wycombe I think, Hampshire at any rate, and - then they got - typhoid fever, and so they moved to the Kent coast. Near Hithe and Sandgate. And - yes, it was - very nic
e spot.
\par I:\tab Did your parents ask you if you wanted to go to boarding school or was it just accepted that you would do anyway?
\par WF:\tab Oh well, everybody went then didn't they. I think so. Nearly everybody.
\par I:\tab Did you want to go, did you look forward to it?
\par WF:\tab Oh I never thought whether I would - wanted to or not, but yes I did look forward to it. Yes. I was told it was a delightful place to go to. I didn't altogether think so when I got there.
\par I:\tab Did you have a uniform do you remember?
\par WF:\tab Oh no. No. Not at a - small school like that.
\par I:\tab How did you feel being at school that was your uncle's, did you have special treatment?
\par WF:\tab Well I seemed to - get off punishments of all kinds there. It was - his - his wife was my aunt, you see, and - and - and - they'd never hit me or whack me or anything of that sort and -
\par I:\tab Did the other boys get whacked?
\par WF:\tab Yes, they did, terribly.
\par I:\tab Was there a lot of whacking?
\par WF:\tab This man. Mm, Mr - he used to beat them with a hunting whip, and - yes, they had. And -
\par I:\tab How old were they when they left there?
\par WF:\tab They were fourteen usually.
\par I:\tab It was a prep school was it?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were the boys happy there on the whole?
\par WF:\tab Well - they were very nice boys there and - they didn't have any bullying or - anything in that sort. And - well the headmaster was - down on all that sort of thing.
\par I:\tab How many boys were there in the school?
\par WF:\tab About thirty. Mm. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of things did they teach you apart from the basic education, were they very insistent on tidiness and punctuality and things like that?
\par WF:\tab It was - oh - oh yes, yes, mm. Yes, you had to - had to be punctual and - supposed to be tidy. Mm.
\par I:\tab And how about ways of speaking and behaving generally?
\par WF:\tab They wouldn't allow any swearing and - that sort of thing
. No. We had to behave well. And - they used to keep an eye on everything, if a boy got - uproarious and wanted to fight anybody - he was - soon reported and - stopped from anything of that sort. So we scored by being - rather strict and - fearsome - in t
hose ways.
\par I:\tab Was it in a big house?
\par WF:\tab It was in one - a fair sized house, With two lodges - fairly large - sleep in dormitories.
\par I:\tab How many boys in each dormitory? About fifteen?
\par WF:\tab About - yes, something like that and - then they - had one or two extr
a - little rooms and - then they built another - another house to - house more boys in. And then - after I left - still another one - which the partner - it was a partnership ultimately, another headmaster came along, and then - he was younger and he took
 it over, and they had a - new place. Yes. The old school was - given over to girls. Mm.
\par I:\tab Can you remember what - was it particularly church?
\par WF:\tab No, it wasn't. Well - we used to have - also the chapel. First in the gym, a part of the gym on a platform pu
t up at one end, and then we had little - special chapel made. And - headmaster's wife used to play - but otherwise if we - didn't go to church very often. No, not to a parish church, I don't - I don't exactly know why but - they had a church of their own
 - mostly. My father didn't think it was quite right. No.
\par I:\tab Did it seem strange to you after your very sort of church background?
\par WF:\tab Mm. Yes. Oh I don't think I worried very much about it. But parents thought it was wrong.
\par I:\tab Do you remember when you were taken to school, did your parents take you?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Or did you go by yourself?
\par WF:\tab No, they - they took us - myself and my brother off to school.
\par I:\tab On the train did you go?
\par WF:\tab Yes, oh yes, there were no cars in those days.
\par I:\tab Your brother went at the same time did he?
\par WF:\tab Brother went at the same time, yes.
\par I:\tab So that was nice, you weren't quite so lonely?
\par WF:\tab No. He stayed there about seven years. Yes. He was seven when he went. Fourteen before he got a scholarship to Eastbourne College. Very good scholarship, sixty pounds, which was enormous in those days.
\par I:\tab Was the academic standard good at this little school?
\par WF:\tab Fairly good, it - wasn't quite - as high as some I think. Well some schools specialise a lot - and - keep in touch with - Eton or 
some great public school - and get tips about exams, I think. And know exactly what to be - what to do, but no, I shouldn't say it was quite the highest - highest standard. They were rather wealthy boys I think of wealthy parents and I don't think they tr
oubled their heads much about scholarships. Yes, yes, yes.
\par I:\tab Can you remember the food you used to have?
\par WF:\tab The food, well - I didn't like the food - very much, but I don't like meat, I don't eat it now too often. Otherwise it was quite good as - as food went, yes.
\par I:\tab Did they make you eat meat?
\par WF:\tab Yes - brutes they were at that, they - made one eat up all the gristle and everything. Put me opposite the headmaster to see that I did it - no escape. Ghastly.
\par I:\tab You had to eat everything did you?
\par WF:\tab Yes, frightful.
\par I:\tab When you were at home did you have to eat up everything?
\par WF:\tab More or less, not quite so strict as that only - no.
\par I:\tab I should think you hated that?
\par WF:\tab I did detest it.
\par I:\tab What did you think of the school, can you remember at the time?
\par WF:\tab Oh I got - I got to like it I think, especially in the - summertime with - cricket going on.
\par I:\tab Did you like games?
\par WF:\tab I liked cricket; I didn't like football at all. Not - soccer football. No.
\par I:\tab Is that what they played there?
\par WF:\tab Yes. I was very good at cricket. Bowling, that sort of thing. But -
\par I:\tab Did your parents come down to see you?
\par WF:\tab No, they never came near us. No. The whole five years I was there - parents - parents - parents wouldn't come - and pay us a visit.
\par I:\tab Why was that?
\par WF:\tab Well they thought it would upset us. And -
\par I:\tab Do you remember ever minding about that?
\par WF:\tab Oh I don't know. It wasn't - it wasn't much good minding. No.
\par I:\tab Did other boy's parents come?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, they - all came. I rather wondered why ours didn't. And - we seemed to be right at the - end of England, end of nowhere. The tip of Kent, it - seemed a long way from all our associations and - relations and people. In those days.
\par I:\tab Did they go on taking you and fetching you from school?
\par WF:\tab No, we - made the journey our
selves. They'd sometimes come up as far as - London, or one of them would, usually father, and - then they'd put us in the hands of - commissioners as they called them, and - they were - retired Crimean veterans mostly.
\par I:\tab Who were they employed by?
\par WF:\tab I don't know who they were - employed by, but they - in a sort of uniform, and - they used to come and - meet us at the station and - take us out to lunch somewhere and then - to see the National Gallery. Some nice place.
\par I:\tab They weren't employed by the railway then?
\par WF:\tab No, they weren't, no.
\par I:\tab Nor the school?
\par WF:\tab No, no. No, they came from Chelsea, they - they were - they were Chelsea Pensioners. Mm. All been in the Crimea, they used to tell us about it.
\par I:\tab Would they have got paid for that?
\par WF:\tab Yes, they'd have been paid.
\par I:\tab This was a sort of service they did?
\par WF:\tab Yes. It was a sort of - service, I don't know whether they still do it now, I don't suppose they do. Everybody goes by car.
\par I:\tab Did you enjoy that day in London?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes, it was - on the - we were on the verge of getting home.
\par I:\tab Did you look forward to the holidays?
\par WF:\tab I should think we did, yes. All the term, yes. I used to count the days.
\par I:\tab Did you have long holidays?
\par WF:\tab No, not very. Well - five or - five weeks at Christmas, three weeks - Easter. Seven in summer. Two days added on each time.
\par I:\tab Were your parents interested in how you were getting on at school?
\par WF:\tab Well they had the report at the end of the term.
\par I:\tab What happened if it was bad?
\par WF:\tab Well it wasn't always true. No.
\par I:\tab Did father read it?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Mm.
\par I:\tab Then did he have a word with you about it or not?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we used to talk about it. It was - all the same it wasn't - it was rather nonsensical. Yes. Mm, I don't think - they didn't know one - really well enough.
\par I:\tab Your teachers?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I - I was a very truthful boy, always spoke the truth, the other boys, a lot of them told lies. Or some of them did and - yes, there was one little boy who was always telling lies, they always believed him and - said I was a very
 bad boy and - when in fact - and he - they used to concoct all sorts of tales, about - misbehaviour.
\par I:\tab Did they not like you?
\par WF:\tab No, I don't suppose they - did very much. I was always - I remember - I don't remember ever - hedging or going round the point, I told the - I used to tell the truth and the others used to make - make up stories.
\par I:\tab Do you think they resented you being a relation of the headmaster?
\par WF:\tab 
I don't know. I think I - I think I scored rather, I mean he was awfully - he was rather brutal and - knocking people about and beating, and - they had a - a dispute once over me in the headmaster said I - was very stupid not to do something or other and 
t
hey - his wife stood - being a B. - stood - stood up for me. So in that way I got let off a - a - and once I was - I was called up for bullying someone and - which I hadn't really done at all, he'd been bullying me, but - he had - they didn't say anything
 to me about it, I was sent up to report my bad behaviour but - I just heard in silence.
\par I:\tab Do you think they were frightened your father would come down?
\par WF:\tab Well they knew it was a - horrid little boy, I'd - I'd just given him - I'd give him - given him a
 smack or a punch or something. And - he probably deserved it I think the headmaster had given him many whacks and apparently you know, think he sympathised with me. No I got on - all right there.
\par I:\tab Were there any gangs in the school do you remember, a group of boys together against other boys?
\par WF:\tab Oh - sometimes, there was a rather - nasty boy with a stiff leg who was - boys with impediments - always - they're apt to be rather nasty aren't they. But otherwise - no, there wasn't anything - much of that sor
t. I was once called up to give witness about - some boys who were - supposed to have treated me badly but - I said they didn't, only mild teasing and just - I - well I was - more Christian than some of them with being brought up in a vicarage, kind of an
imals and that sort of thing, we - I think -
\par I:\tab They were not?
\par WF:\tab Well I thought not.
\par I:\tab What did you think of them, because you hadn't really met many English boys before that had you?
\par WF:\tab No. Well some were very very nice - one can sort out the nice boys.
\par I:\tab Did you have a special friend?
\par WF:\tab I had a friend who - French boy for a - rather special friend once, I - at that school.
\par I:\tab French was he?
\par WF:\tab Yes. I always - went after foreigners. Yes. In the army I was - when I was in the Great War stretcher bear
ing I was best friends with a - Welsh Nationalist who - was very naughty fellow really, burnt down a lot of army huts afterwards. I oughtn't to have been a friend of his, but I always - sympathised with those sort of people. And a Scotsman. But -
\par I:\tab When you left your little school you were fourteen?
\par WF:\tab Fourteen I was then.
\par I:\tab And you went to then to Kings?
\par WF:\tab I tried to get a scholarship at Eton of all places. Of course I - I couldn't get that. Then I went to St Edwards's school. Mm.
\par I:\tab That's at Cambridge is it?
\par WF:\tab That's at Oxford. Yes. That's a - a pretty good school now I think, but it was - only starting when I went there, at least it was - fairly small.
\par I:\tab Did you get a scholarship to there?
\par WF:\tab I got a scholarship there, yes, forty pounds. A fair amount in those days.
\par I:\tab Did you feel your parents were having to sacrifice to send you to these schools or not?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Oh yes. Well they - I was - they gave me to understand they were, of course they things were so different in those days. Mm. Prices an
d everything were very different. I think they had a fairly hard time. Because - we - had the wretched system of - having to track round for the tithe. And the farmers never wanted to pay it, and - then they don't - don't know whether they - ever got thei
r proper stipends. So I mean you - probably they did have a hard time. And they only had about - they had about three hundred or so a year, that had to be - waited for and looked for.
\par I:\tab And they had quite an establishment to keep up didn't they?
\par WF:\tab Yes. W
ell you - we had to - entertain practically almost the whole parish. All the children and places come and be entertained - I think - well Sunday school and that meant - every child in the place, it was different then. We entertained all the various - chur
ch organisations, ringers - there are not any of them now hardly any, as far as I can see, and - choirs.
\par I:\tab Did your parents have their own friends, their own personal friends?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of people would they have been?
\par WF:\tab Oh we used to - visit round much more in those days I think than they do now.
\par I:\tab What kind of people, the local aristocracy?
\par WF:\tab Local aristocracy partly and - and local - vicars and - curates which they used to have in those days. They used to - have them
 in at Christmas, and - play horses on the floor. Terrifically - very childish. Well we were young when we first went to - but the - one or two visits and letters that I've had from these people - since, lately they've - they've said - and it's very nice 
of them to say so, how much - how much nicer it was in those days when we were - all one family, I suppose it was in a way. In a village, yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember when you were at home if your parents didn't like you to play with certain children, were they particular about who?
\par WF:\tab No, no, I don't think they - we didn't see so very much of the - children round about, no, I don't remember.
\par I:\tab In the school holidays you just played at home did you?
\par WF:\tab Mm. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab But they didn't tell you expressly not to go and play with the village children?
\par WF:\tab No, I don't think - no. No, we were very friendly with them. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have dinner parties, do you remember your parents having dinner parties?
\par WF:\tab Yes, yes. We had dinner parties, yes, sometimes. Mm. Beer and that sort of thing. Except that we had to be - all teetotallers in those days because - there was a cam - a campaign against drunkenness. But we used to get in drinks for -
\par I:\tab What would they be offered?
\par WF:\tab They were - oh beer mostly or possibly cider I think. Beer mainly. They seemed to enjoy. And wine sometimes. Which I thought very wonderful.
\par I:\tab So there were a lot of people coming in and out of the vicarage were there?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes, there were, yes, oh we used to have - used to go round calling in the neighbourhood in - little pony cart. Mm.
\par I:\tab You children were taken were you?
\par WF:\tab Yes, were taken. I never - I never even had a horse of my own or rode about like I did - when I was abroad on Norfolk Island.
\par I:\tab Did you miss that?
\par WF:\tab Yes, very much and they taught us dancing at school which I didn't like at all and -
\par I:\tab Which school?
\par WF:\tab That was the - Kent school, yes. And I - I wanted riding - seemed much more to the point.
\par I:\tab You danced with each other did you?
\par WF:\tab Danced - with each other. About three little girls used to come in from the neighbourhood.
\par I:\tab You didn't think much of that at that age?
\par WF:\tab No.
\par I:\tab At your little school what was your favourite lesson?
\par WF:\tab Well - geography - I think, and - then we had a scientific lesson too which amused me very much.
\par I:\tab Why?
\par WF:\tab Doing funny little experiments. With - rubbing a - fountain pen, which we had then against some - cloth, and making it pick up bits of paper. Experimented with - with a pen - pendulum, which was made to me
asure a yard and that sort of thing. But I liked geography very much because I was good at that. Because I'd travelled and that sort of beat everybody else. Place names and countries, rivers and that and mountains and things.
\par I:\tab Did you find it very different when you got to St Edwards?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes, very different there.
\par I:\tab A bigger school?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, three times the size, about a hundred boys then, it's got much bigger since.
\par I:\tab What was the emphasis there?
\par WF:\tab There we - it was all Latin and Greek in
 those days. No - nothing else seemed to matter at all. Headmaster came and - gave instruction on the Bible every week. But he was very foolish, he - he let the boys play about all - I hated - hated the whole thing because I - naturally had respect for th
e Bible and - he ought to have - come now, treat it very severely. And some of the fellows - said most dreadful, wicked, blasphemous things. I didn't like that part of it at all. And -
\par I:\tab Was it a spartan sort of school or was it quite comfortable?
\par WF:\tab Oh - was sparse - spartan sort of school yes, the most spartan I should think in England. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What was spartan about it?
\par WF:\tab Well we had no warm water or hot water at all at any time. And - we were kept in order, beaten out. Yes. Yes. I had a whack - whacking before I'd been there a fortnight. Mm.
\par I:\tab What did you do?
\par WF:\tab Oh just didn't notice something, hadn't been - I supposed to clear up the classroom before the - les - before the lesson. I forgot this, I got beaten for that. They were always whacking people.
\par I:\tab For quite small things?
\par WF:\tab Yes. I got whacked for a thing that someone else had done - another time.
\par I:\tab Did you tell them someone else had done it?
\par WF:\tab No. Used to - great deal of emphasis on the discipline. I can't think what'll happen now that the headmaster doesn't believe in any - corporal punishment goes there 'cos that was the - sort of how they kept the place together I think.
\par I:\tab They were quite big boys by then?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes. Oh they had to be - severe as far as I cold see, the sort of boys - that were about then.
\par I:\tab Were they from the same sort of families as your other school?
\par WF:\tab No, they weren't at all the same sort of families, they - they were much poorer families and - half of them were from parson's families. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Not so well behaved?
\par WF:\tab No, not particularly, no. Don't think so, rather worse - no, they weren't they were - I don't think they were so well behaved as the - first lot of boys I was with. Rather rough sort of boys.
\par I:\tab Were you cold in the school, cold in bed?
\par WF:\tab Oh frightfully, yes. Mm. Those were frightfully cold places.
\par I:\tab What about the food?
\par WF:\tab Oh it wasn't - I do think - didn't think it was very good there. At breakfast you had some sort of stilly they'd call it almost I think.
\par I:\tab What was that?
\par WF:\tab A so
rt of porridge that - was very - not very appetising, you know, sloshy, messy. And - and great chunks of white bread and butter which wasn't really very - hygienic I don't think, the - we never had - any - any other course for breakfast which - I think my
 
brother had. Never had any eggs or anything to brighten up breakfast. Then - lunch we just - had very sloshy potatoes and - stringy meat. But things weren't very well - not very good. The evening - in the evening nothing but bread and butter again. This -
 very - thick pieces, very thinly scraped over. It was a rather poor school.
\par I:\tab Were the boys healthy?
\par WF:\tab No, I don't think the schoolboys ever seemed very healthy. No. Don't know whether schoolgirls are. No, I don't think they always looked scabby to me and pimply. Mm.
\par I:\tab Do you remember a lot of them going sick?
\par WF:\tab Yes - every now and then. I don't think it was a sufficient diet. And - it - the life wasn't - very hygienic either. We had an indoor - an outdoor swimming bath, I suppose that was - something
, but - when I first went there we didn't even have soap to - not the - main part of the body. Just - just cold water, yes, diving in and out and - about - twenty towels - among a hundred boys, yes. So you can - so - I always stayed in the water a good lo
ng time, when I came out the towels were nearly black. And thin. Yes. I just put my clothes on and - streaming, I was wet all over. Amazingly survived it all.
\par I:\tab Did your parents know about this?
\par WF:\tab Yes, well it was a struggling school and - a much more en
lightened headmaster came to to it - in my second term, and he insisted that every boy should - have something extra for breakfast besides this very thin porridge and - bread and scrape, and - and - saw that - that - that the bating arrangements and washi
ng arrangements were much better. Everyone had a clean towel, there was - of his own, which was - well there was an outburst - an outbreak of ringworm all over the school. Yes. Which is - head ringworm.
\par I:\tab That's because of unhygienic things?
\par WF:\tab It is, yes
, and - well I don't know, that wasn't all over the school, there was an outbreak of ringworm and - you know, not right about that, some of the boys got it and had to be segregated. Yes. And we used to see them walking about themselves, all over the place
 and - keep away from them. Yes, like lepers, yes. And after that - all headgear was banned, we - started going about without our hats, as I still do, or a cap. It - it's quite a good idea to let the sun in on your head.
\par WF:\tab Did you have to wear a uniform there?
\par I:\tab Well were expected to wear rather dark coloured things. And - that - that was all and - no, not a uniform really.
\par WF:\tab Did your parents come to see you at this school?
\par I:\tab Oh yes, they were always coming.
\par WF:\tab They liked that school?
\par I:\tab Yes, they liked the school and they liked to be - come up to Oxford. Mm. Was your brother there too?
\par WF:\tab Yes. No, he wasn't there, he was at Eastbourne. Yes. Yes. I - gathered Eastbourne was much more comfortable and - a nice school it was. But still -
\par I:\tab Do you think the education was good at your school?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I think it was pretty good, I think the headmaster was a very good teacher. He used to - I was in the sixth form, top form - I think nearly half the time I was there, and - I got in contact with him quite a l
ot and - I used to be entranced at his teaching, and - his - classes - ancient history lessons were - were awfully - interesting. Mm. He used to give talks about the - use of sea power and that sort of thing, how the Greek ships rammed into the Persian sh
ips and I found it great fun as most boys do - like that sort of - sort of thing.
\par I:\tab Were they all masters, no women teachers in those days?
\par WF:\tab No. No, there ware no women teachers, no, none at all.
\par I:\tab Were the other masters good did you think?
\par WF:\tab No, they were - none none of them were quite so different again who were quite so good. They were a long way behind I think, the - even the best one.
\par I:\tab Did they have a reasonable standard of living or were they poorly paid do you think?
\par WF:\tab Oh - oh I thin
k they got about a hundred and fifty a year. Mm, yes. Think I think that's - that's about all. Headmaster used to get about four hundred a year in those days. Mm. But he is - he is a very fine man, the - the one that I was with. He was - oh he was a very 
fine man, he's - got a very high standard and he taught us all the - best things and - he was very religious and - and I think - I think for - a lot of them - for some reason or other - couldn't bear him, I don't know why that was. I liked him very much.

\par I:\tab Do you think he had a lot of influence on you?
\par WF:\tab Oh rather, yes, yes.
\par I:\tab More than your father, do you think?
\par WF:\tab Well he did in a way. He - had me up to his room and he - he said - he knew my character exactly, he said - well you won't be - I can't see
 that you'll be good - at anything - you won't be good as a teacher and - you won't enjoy it much if you go abroad in some government post. And I said, well - whatever can I do then, I shant get any - and he said - said to me - well the - it's not you, it
'
s Jesus Christ that will help you. And he said, if you - get to know Jesus Christ and follow him, believe in him, he'll - you can do anything. It was a wonderful thing for a - master to say so I - I said, well - it's all right then. There's - there's a wa
y - secret - that's the secret of life, he said, yes. And he persuaded me - used to take us out for walks and we started off on a walk, I used to walk with him sometimes, and he persuaded me to take up - the profession I have taken up. Mm. Yes.
\par I:\tab And so you decided to go to Leeds?
\par WF:\tab Yes, Leeds Clergy School.
\par I:\tab How did you come to go there?
\par WF:\tab Well we met - I met the - principle of the clergy school, he was - a don at my college at Cambridge. And -
\par I:\tab Which was your college?
\par WF:\tab College.
\par I:\tab Is that a theological college?
\par WF:\tab No, it's just a - it was just one of the colleges, I don't think there's much - difference. That way. Some have more than others but - it - hadn't got a lot of - very much emphasis I always thought. So I'm - annoyed with the college n
ow because - I think it's not been true to its - traditions.
\par I:\tab If you weren't any good at anything how did you get to university?
\par WF:\tab Well - I was quite good at - I'd got - I was a good scholar in the main, I was fairly good, and - I very nearly got a sch
olarship to - up to Cambridge, an exhibition. And then - I wanted - to go abroad, be a missionary somewhere, and he said, well if you want to do that - be a missionary we'll - we've got funds that will help you. And they got - me funds amounting to - over
 
seventy pounds a year. And - missionary funds. From various quarters. And they said, you can - set out and you've got those on your own merits because - you're near enough - to a scholarship - to merit them. As I - yes, oh yes, so I had that and I - I kep
t that seventy pounds a year - all through my spell at Cambridge.
\par I:\tab How long were you there?
\par WF:\tab Three years. Another year at Leeds Theological College. All the time I had that help. Yes. Parents only had - my father and mother had gone by then but - my pa
rents only had - about thirty pounds a year to find. Fees in those days were about a - hundred a year I think at Cambridge.
\par I:\tab Did you like the university life?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes, I liked it - very much, yes, very much indeed.
\par I:\tab Did you work hard or did you have a good time as well?
\par WF:\tab No, I had - I didn't work at all in - that sense. There were too many distractions there. There was all the social life and - there was the - the sports too and - and then we were very keen - missionaries there then. And - I 
used to go to their meetings. But I didn't settle to - to anything you could call work really.
\par I:\tab Did you get a degree?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I just got the degree but - I should have got an honours degree, I only got a pass degree. But still it doesn't make -
\par I:\tab Do you regret that or do you think you made the most of the life of the university?
\par WF:\tab I used to regret it, I - don't think it - makes much difference now. But - oh but - difficulties about settling down at the university.
\par I:\tab Did you have girlfriends?
\par WF:\tab No. No. No, I never - never got on with girls. My brother did but - although - it's different from those days. Oh I like the girls now. They seem to be -
\par I:\tab I suppose you had to be introduced before you cold speak to any of them?
\par WF:\tab Oh goodness yes. Stupid, dreadful, silly, I wouldn't go back to those days that sort of thing.
\par I:\tab Were there many girls in the university?
\par WF:\tab Well there was a girl's college about a hundred yards from us. We used to meet one of them sometimes. A young lady called Miss Scott u
sed to come into our rooms. Nellie Scott, yes, I - yes, we had - we had some contact with them, I shouldn't have said we had nothing to do with them. A nice girl, and we knew the people in the - in the town a bit, and - used to meet the - townspeople some
times. Mm. It was very different from these days.
\par I:\tab Can you remember how people were divided into classes, how did you think of them, in different levels?
\par WF:\tab Well, the - used to be the - class of people we called the poor who were - earned about eighteen shillings a week. And I suppose there were - middle class people like ourselves.
\par I:\tab Were there people like tradesmen between the poor and yourselves?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I suppose there were really, there were - the village people who lived very primitively. And - th
e - had nothing compared with what - everybody has now. Don't think they had any baths or - certainly didn't have washing machines or cars. Not even bicycles a lot of them. Very primitive sort.
\par I:\tab How about people who kept shops?
\par WF:\tab Yes, then there was - that sort of class of people.
\par I:\tab Did you feel they were comfortably off financially?
\par WF:\tab Yes, yes, I think they were. Well they could earn what they liked really.
\par I:\tab But they were below you in social scale were they?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I suppose they thought they we
re in those days. Yes, they - we used to have sort - sort of three strata in the place. The - the labouring class, the - the farmers, and - schoolmasters and those sort of people. Then the big man who lived in the big house.
\par I:\tab Which one did you belong to?
\par WF:\tab Well they were - we mustn't belong to any - class, you aren't supposed to but we - I suppose we did really.
\par I:\tab Which one did you feel you belonged to?
\par WF:\tab Oh it - I think we thought we were upper class. But - we - we - we weren't really, I mean we - lived along very differently from the - people in the - big houses.
\par I:\tab But you were invited to their houses?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes, we were, yes, we - yes, we met them as equals. And so it didn't make - much difference really. There were - very wealthy people in those days about, great - much greater - distinctions of wealth and property. That sort of thing.

\par I:\tab What sort of people did you call the poor people, were they very much tied by their employers in the village, did they depend very much on them?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I - yes, I think - think they did. 'Cos they - they didn't have very many needs. They got things frightfully cheaply. I never thought they - paid the same sort of prices as other people did, we did.
\par I:\tab You mean they got things from the farms?
\par WF:\tab Yes, they got a lot from the farms. I think from the shops they had - must have had preference on all sorts of - prices.
\par I:\tab Were they respectful to you and your family?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Oh frightfully, yes.
\par I:\tab Did they touch their caps?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, rather, or pulled their - forelocks and - little girls bobbed up and down, which I don't see being - much of nowadays. No.
\par I:\tab Did they do that to you to?
\par WF:\tab Yes, yes.
\par I:\tab How were you known in the village?
\par WF:\tab They used to - they used to call me Master Frank - Master Fra
nk and my brother Master Jack. They used to pull their forelocks or - bob - bob up and down if they meet us. And - one vicar told them not to do that I - but I - I thought he was wrong, I mean they seemed to enjoy being polite, it was - the way they thoug
ht of being polite I suppose.
\par I:\tab Who was the most important man in the village?
\par WF:\tab Oh - well I don't know, father possibly. Yes. But there's a big man employed a lot of - Welshmen of course, Welsh extract who ran big works, big engineering works and they're all - all over the world I think, Allan lived in our village.
\par I:\tab Was he respected in the same way?
\par WF:\tab Yes, oh I suppose they had to, they - there were none - not very many strikes and that sort of thing then, they were only - just beginning I think. And
 - I used to - support the strikes in my mind and - I got up a contribution once to help the - families. Mm.
\par I:\tab What sort of people - do you remember a chapel at all anywhere?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we had the Wesleyan chapel as they called it then.
\par I:\tab What sort of people, what was the difference between people who went to church and those who went to chapel?
\par WF:\tab Well I don't think there's much difference, there's any - particular difference.
\par I:\tab Was there a class difference?
\par WF:\tab No I don't think so. The chapel minister w
as - wasn't like the present ones who - dress themselves up like us, he was - he might be a grocer or - he wasn't an educated man in those days. And - he didn't - wear any sign of office, now he goes about with his collar on and - yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of people would go to his chapel?
\par WF:\tab Oh - there's an old Yorkshire lady - called Lunt Liz by everybody was - a great - important person there, great leader in the chapel. We used to meet there sometimes, go and have services with them. We weren't so stand offish as -
\par I:\tab There was communication between you?
\par WF:\tab I think so - I think - better communication perhaps than there is now. In some ways. My father used to - used to say sometimes, if you want anything done - go to the Wesleyans as they called them then, go t
o the - nonconformists. Mm. And then they'd add up - I think the church people are really the best but - they're rather slow and - chapel people are - more go-ahead. Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, they did. I don't know what they got their - salaries from. I su
ppose from collections from these - poor people.
\par I:\tab Did you feel that the Wesleyans minister was on the same level as your father socially?
\par WF:\tab No, I didn't think - didn't quite think that, no.
\par I:\tab Did your parents have the same sort of attitude towards social class or were they different in their attitudes?
\par WF:\tab Mm - well they had the same - everybody had the same sort of attitude then.
\par I:\tab Mother and father agreed on matters of class?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes. I think so, yes. It didn't mix them up, you couldn't, but we entertained them all from time to time. At parties - for them all. Mm. You have to keep in touch with everybody.
\par I:\tab Would you say your father worked hard at his job?
\par WF:\tab Oh tremendously hard, yes. Yes, well he had so many jobs. Vicar of th
e Parish. He was chaplain of a - well one of these - waifs and strays home, girl's homes as they called it in those days. And - and chaplain of - it was called the Shephers for girls who'd gone astray. So - he had a lot of - organisations he was intereste
d in, then his - commissary to the Bishop of London Esher. He - had a tremendous lot of work there.
\par I:\tab He was a very active man then?
\par WF:\tab Was very active, he travelled about a lot, although all over the place giving lectures on - mission, and - kept - keepi
ng in touch and seeing people who wanted to go there. They used to come round and see him. He was always at work on something in his study or - parish or - going abroad, he had - tremendous lot of work and influence in the neighbouring town, Bedford. Mm. 
And - almost all the organisations in the town he kept in touch with. I don't - I only do it, there in Banbury for instance, never had - lived by the back boundary for long time.
\par I:\tab He must have been a very busy man?
\par WF:\tab Yes, he was very busy indeed, yes, yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have a policeman in your village?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes, yeah, res - resident policeman. Had a cottage there.
\par I:\tab Was he a friend or an enemy?
\par WF:\tab Oh a great friend - oh I think so, yes. Don't remember very much about him though.
\par I:\tab Was there much crime in the village?
\par WF:\tab No, I don't - drunkenness, that sort of thing. And they got drunk - the men got drunk on Saturday nights. Not the women I think very much, there were one or two cases. One place a - young girl came in with bruises all over her body a
nd she'd been beaten up. Mm. By a drunken old lady. Mm. Yes. There were these whacks over her - her shoulders. Yes. Yes, there were - there were - that sort of thing went on occasionally. Children were - occasionally - neglected or ill-treated.
\par I:\tab Can you remember your birthday, was it usually at home or at school?
\par WF:\tab It's at school I think always was yes, November the tenth. St Martins Eve. I was born - St Martins Even in St Martin's Parish - my father was rector of St Martins Parish and my - grandma othe
r was - patron. And then they were going to call me Martin.
\par I:\tab Would you have liked to have bean called Martin?
\par WF:\tab Yes I would. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have a good birthday at school, did they make anything special of it?
\par WF:\tab No, no. No, I don't think the school knew anything - didn't think the school - school would know anything about it.
\par I:\tab Wouldn't know when your birthday was?
\par WF:\tab No I don't think so.
\par I:\tab Did your parents send you presents?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes - yes, they - they would. Well I suppose in my prep school, they were my own relations, I suppose they - made a fuss, perhaps made a - made a bit of fuss. And -
\par I:\tab You didn't have a birthday cake or anything?
\par WF:\tab Oh no, no. Don't remember - no, I can't - can't remember having any presents.
\par I:\tab Could you describe to me Christmas at home?
\par WF:\tab Oh that was as I said, that's very much a parish - affair. He - had the Holy Communion in the morning. All the parish turned up everybody - who could, Holy Communion.
\par I:\tab Was that early service?
\par WF:\tab Yes. And -
 we had functions - first half of Christmas Day, with the - the children coming - coming in. And - I think their got oranges and that sort of thing. And then the - second half of the day we - we kept to ourselves. Had - functions at home.
\par I:\tab What sort of things would you do?
\par WF:\tab Well - playing horses. On the floor.
\par I:\tab And presents did you have?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes. Yes. The postman used to stagger round on Christmas morning - in the snow if there was any snow, there wasn't usually - with - simply loaded with - prese
nts which - he had to walk - he had to walk on foot with, loaded with all these - things, he must have - hated - Christmas morning I should think.
\par I:\tab Did you have a lot of presents at Christmas time?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes, well the post used to get in about eleven instead of about eight. Yes, so weighted down with this load.
\par I:\tab Did he come in for a drink?
\par WF:\tab No, I don't remember the postman - other people did - ring us and - choir singers. Then we had parties for everybody - body, on or about Christmas.
\par I:\tab Did you have your own Christmas dinner or lunch?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes.
\par I:\tab Which did you have, an evening one?
\par WF:\tab Evening - evening always, yes. Well we had services up 'til midday.
\par I:\tab Did you have the traditional Christmas dinner?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I think we did, yes. Always - turkey as far as I remember, plum pudding and mince pies. Always got ill after it. A hearty meal I should think. Yes, eat too much.
\par I:\tab Were you a musical family at all?
\par WF:\tab No, my mother was pretty musical, yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have musical evenings singing together?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, we had - had them, yes.
\par I:\tab Did father join in?
\par WF:\tab He couldn't sing much. No. And - I don't remember him singing at this sort of - evenings. It's - he did sometimes at parish affairs at weddings and - things of that sort it just wasn't
 - the old fashioned songs in those days. Yes, 'Timothy White was a Cheesemongers Boy', and that sort of thing.
\par I:\tab The what?
\par WF:\tab 'Timothy White was a Cheesemonger's Boy' and - silly things. And 'There Were Three Sailors of 
Bristol City'. And - but mother was - she was the - one for - singing, and played very beautifully. Yes. And sing - contralto, and she used to get - singers - people who could sing to come in, any gentlemen as a rule who fancied their voices. That was at 
Norfolk Island too a lot. In England. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you children sing?
\par WF:\tab No, I don't think we - well, we could just - sang easy songs.
\par I:\tab Where you in a choir at all?
\par WF:\tab At - at home, not - not at school.
\par I:\tab You were at home?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have to be?
\par WF:\tab No, we didn't have to be anything we - were very very loyal, not like - children nowadays. We'd never - never miss a service at church or - don't always keep up to that now but -
\par I:\tab Did you play any - games at home in the family?
\par WF:\tab Yes, well we - played - cricket about the place and -
\par I:\tab Card games at all?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, we had - we used to play card games, yes. Chiefly whist I think, we didn't - we didn't get on to bridge, but - we had - we had to rely on our own sources, you - couldn't turn t
he wireless on. You had to invent all sorts of games or - heaps of games we used to have. Mm. Consequences and - all sorts of things, Beg o'my neighbour - heads, boeis and legs and drawing games, historical games. Drawing scenes and guessing them. All tha
t sort of thing has gone out. Do nothing but turn on the wireless now.
\par I:\tab I expect there were a lot of books in your house were there?
\par WF:\tab Yes - quite a lot of books. And -
\par I:\tab Was your father a great reader?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes, read a good bit. He had - prizes from Eton College and those sort of places - I've got some of them still new.
\par I:\tab He read them did he?
\par WF:\tab I don't know that he read them very much, he was usually engaged on the latest book out, he was - very much up to date.
\par I:\tab How about your mother, did she read?
\par WF:\tab I don't think she did very much.
\par I:\tab Newspapers did you have, magazines?
\par WF:\tab We had a - paper, the 'Daily Mail'. That's about all.
\par I:\tab No magazines, no women's magazines?
\par WF:\tab No, I don't think - don't remember them. Considered ourselves very p
oor in those days. Whether we were - so badly off I - don't know, it - seems to me that they're much - more prosperous days for people like ourselves than - these days - than recent days have been. Not so bad now. Money went further.
\par I:\tab Did your mother read aloud to you or your father when you were very little?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, father used to read. Tennyson sometimes and used to -
\par I:\tab Tennyson?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we used to call for it.
\par I:\tab You liked it did you?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes. Loved it - the death of Arthur, passing of Arthur.
\par I:\tab No children's books?
\par WF:\tab Well the Just So Stories and - Rudyard Kipling. About all.
\par I:\tab Can you remember a funeral, your father must have officiated at many funerals?
\par WF:\tab Mm.
\par I:\tab Did you ever remember going to one? Can you tell me what they were like?
\par WF:\tab I didn't go very much to funerals. Went to our mother's. Rather weepy things as far as I can remember. People crying. But I -
\par I:\tab Did everyone dress in black?
\par WF:\tab Oh much - yes, more than they do now. Wore arm - arm bands, black armband
s - for some time after. When my - my mother passed on it was beginning to alter, there was less of - that sort of outward - rather - showy sort of mourning. Of course they had a tremendous lot in France, especially among Roman Catholics didn't they, thos
e
 days. Dreadful - looking things, they - awful looking coaches and - black over - with black ribbons and decorations, dreadful, but - that sort of thing gradually - went out and - there were so many killed in the war, in the Great War weren't there. Funer
al and deaths - became - all too familiar.
\par I:\tab What sort of holidays did you have as a child, do you remember?
\par WF:\tab Holidays from school.
\par I:\tab Going away with your parents?
\par WF:\tab Oh going, away, yes. Yes, we - we started - a bit of going off to the seaside, and bathe - swimming and -
\par I:\tab How long would you have gone for?
\par WF:\tab About a month. I think it was. Had a good time. About three Sundays usually.
\par I:\tab Where did you go usually?
\par WF:\tab Went out - the north coast of Norfolk. That's a most vilely - cold part. Yes. Took a cottage, a rented cottage there, which we shared with the inhabitants. Yes.
\par I:\tab They looked after you?
\par WF:\tab Yes, they gave us meals and -
\par I:\tab And you all went together did you?
\par WF:\tab All - all went together. Didn't like it very much, it was - very rough and tumble.
\par I:\tab Would Bank Holidays have been anything special far you do you remember?
\par WF:\tab No, noth - nothing special. Sometimes went off for a bike ride.
\par I:\tab What as a Saturday like at home?
\par WF:\tab Well - well Saturday was getting ready for Sunday. Didn't cook any meals on Sunday. It all had to be got ready on - on Saturday. Didn't have a roast dinner - in the middle of the day in those days. Everything cold.
\par I:\tab Did you have best clothes on Sundays
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes, always.
\par I:\tab And you kept them on all day?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Everybody did.
\par I:\tab How many times a day did you have to go to church when you were little?
\par WF:\tab We didn't have to go at all, we - no, we - we went of our own accord.
\par I:\tab How many times did you go of your own accord then?
\par WF:\tab Three - three times - well when we were quite small twice. Later on three times.
\par I:\tab Was it Sunday school that you went to?
\par WF:\tab No, we didn't go to Sunday school.
\par I:\tab Was there a Sunday school?
\par WF:\tab There was Sunday school but - the schoolmaster took it but - with our parents I suppose that - we knew as much about it as - the schoolmaster.
\par I:\tab Were you allowed to play games or lark about on a Sunday or were your father and mother strict about that?
\par WF:\tab Well father was - actually always in favour of - Sunday cricket on Sunday afternoon, he always - thought it would be a much better way of spending time than - the way these village louts and youths do - did spend it in those days.
\par I:\tab So he didn't mind if you played games?
\par WF:\tab No. Well we actually didn't. Because it didn't seem to be the custom. But -
\par I:\tab What did you do then when you weren't at church?
\par WF:\tab Well went for walks and - looked at the - the - river and the bathing place and had a nice swim, we were awfully fond of swimming. Mm.
\par I:\tab But you wouldn't have a swim on a Sunday?
\par WF:\tab No, we didn't have a swim on a Sunday. Did at school always.
\par I:\tab Did your father say grace at meals?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes, before and after. Mm.
\par I:\tab You were encouraged to say your prayers at night were you?
\par WF:\tab Yes, yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have family prayers?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we did, yes. And in our family it was always prayers at night. Some it was - in the morning but we always had them at night.
\par I:\tab Was your father a political man, was he interested in politics?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes.
\par I:\tab What were his politics?
\par WF:\tab He always voted Conservative. Mm.
\par I:\tab And your mother the same?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we all did I think. I was told at school that it - it was the thing to do and - I always believed that. Before - before I went to school - before
 they had an election, had an election at - when I was at school, I professed to be a Liberal I remember. I was told that wasn't the right thing. It's quite a respectable thing to be as a matter of fact.
\par I:\tab Why did you think you wanted to be a Liberal?
\par WF:\tab Well I - I - thought - that most people were Liberals and - it seemed a very good thing to be and -
\par I:\tab Was your mother interested in politics on her own account?
\par WF:\tab No I don't think very much, no.
\par I:\tab Did she follow what father did?
\par WF:\tab Yes, yes. Generally I think.
\par I:\tab Do you remember them voting in a general election?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I remember - remember one election - about - 1900 or so I think it was - and all the village voted Liberal in those days, and - and - they talked to us about maids in the - maids the
 house and - and - all the ordinary people who were Liberals - were Liberals and so - we thought we were - but -
\par I:\tab You thought you were?
\par WF:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab But you weren't?
\par WF:\tab No. We were terribly - we used to be Conservatives, well - yes, I think - Liberals mostly - non-church non - mostly non-conformist people I think. It's rather political isn't it? Well it is all politics I suppose.
\par I:\tab Was there any influence from the squire in the village or did your father have any influence over what the people voted?
\par WF:\tab Mm.
\par I:\tab Did he try to encourage them to vote one way or another do you think?
\par WF:\tab No he didn't, no. No, he used to preach - a sermon about it at election time. But - telling them to - follow their consciences. No, he didn't - persuade them one way or the o
ther. He - used to say - I shall vote according to my own ways, you must all - make up your own - minds, we went to all the - meetings. Mm. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were they exciting?
\par WF:\tab No. Very quiet things. Mm. The Liberal man, he - came from Nottingham, he rea
lly told - he really mislead the people because he - he used - he was a Nottingham lace manufacturer, and he lived at Nottingham, I couldn't quite see why we should - govern from Nottingham, and - the Conservative was usually a local person, he told - the
y were lace making - community in those days, they told the people that he'd get them market for their lace, of course he wouldn't, he was a -
\par I:\tab If they voted for him?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Of course he couldn't, he was a - they made lace in - in factories and mills an
d - nothing to do with those village people who made hand lace. Yes, they - rather took notice of him. Of course he also - Liberals also in those days they - were in favour of free trade, no tariffs, no - what do you call them, no taxes on - imported - ye
s, no - what do call them, no rev - no - no revenues from imported things and no - be much cheaper.
\par I:\tab Did they have difficulty in selling their lace?
\par WF:\tab Can't think what they did with it. They used to sell it I think sometimes. Very beautiful - handmade lace.
\par I:\tab You were telling me that your father used to be quite involved in other things other than church, other charities?
\par WF:\tab Yes, mostly - church organisations.
\par I:\tab Did your mother have any interests outside the house?
\par WF:\tab Well - not a - she knew people in the village and she - helped them, take things. Do them rice puddings and things of that sort. Oh well I suppose - they were more needy than they are now.
\par I:\tab So she looked after them a bit?
\par WF:\tab Yes. They got no help from the government, or very little - in any case.
\par I:\tab Did she ever go out by herself in the evenings, would she have any sort of friends of her own that she'd go and visit?
\par WF:\tab I don't think so. No, don't think she - occasionally she - she'd go to a dance or something of the sort with a neighbour that - Mm.
\par I:\tab With father?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes. I think so, I -
\par I:\tab They enjoyed that did they?
\par WF:\tab Yes. I think they went together.
\par I:\tab Was father a sporting man at all?
\par WF:\tab No.
\par I:\tab But he liked cricket?
\par WF:\tab No, he - not good any - any sports, not cricket or -
\par I:\tab Never went racing?
\par WF:\tab Oh goodness no. Well he came from a racing sporting family but he never was interested himself, no, not really.
\par I:\tab He never had a bet?
\par WF:\tab No. No, didn't get that amount interested.
\par I:\tab Do you remember if your family was involved in any sort of savings club?
\par WF:\tab Well there's a - there's a clothing club in the place. And - they all put about a penny a week I think. Old fashioned penny.
\par I:\tab Did your father run it?
\par WF:\tab We all ran - well mother I think looked after it.
\par I:\tab But you as a family didn't ever belong to it?
\par WF:\tab No, no. No.
\par I:\tab Were there any insurance's or sick things?
\par WF:\tab I'm not sure. A sick benefit club, no, I don't think we - had anything to do with that sort of thing, and the - other societies, Oddfellow groups and - Free Forrester's there was.
\par I:\tab Do you remember going to any theatres or concerts or music halls when you were young?
\par WF:\tab Oh - yes, we went to the theatre.
\par I:\tab Did you like it?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Thrilled with it, yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Would you have gone regularly?
\par WF:\tab Well we went at - in the winter round about Christmas.
\par I:\tab Father and mother went too did they?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes, we all went, yes. Oh they were thrill - thrilling things. 'Prisoner of Zenda' and - 'Monsieur Beaucare'. All those sort of things.
\par I:\tab How about music hall, were you ever allowed to go to that?
\par WF:\tab No, I don't think we - we just had - I don't remember much of that, but we had a muse - musical festivals at - in the town, I think, Bedford, occasionally.
\par I:\tab Did you have any pocket money when you were young?
\par WF:\tab Yes, we had - took back about five shillings to school. Little more.
\par I:\tab Did you have any to spend at home in the holidays?
\par WF:\tab Yes, about that sort of amount, I think we had to ask for it usually. They didn't go about - scattering pound notes as they children do and -
\par I:\tab What did you spend your money on, do you remember?
\par WF:\tab On - model ships and trains and - steam engines.
\par I:\tab Sweets?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes. And sometimes gave - quite a lot to - some needy - cause, like victims of an earthquake. Mm. Gave up to about a pound. Yes.
\par I:\tab Of your own money?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I gave a pound a Christmas present which I'd just received, went straight into - offertory at Christmas. Pound. Yes.
\par I:\tab Can we talk a bit about your clergy school?
\par WF:\tab Oh, that at Leeds.
\par I:\tab You went there in?
\par WF:\tab 19 - 11. Yes.
\par I:\tab Can you tell me a bit about it, what it was like there?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Well we - there were about twenty or thirty of us, thirty I think, we had the - old Mayor's house, at Leeds, the Mayor of Leeds had originally lived there. And -
\par I:\tab Was it in the centre of the town?
\par WF:\tab Yes, right in the centre, yes. And on a hill, you could look down - practically the whole smoky town. Very smoky those Yorkshire towns were. And - well we - got up about seven and - 
had a service every morning. Morning Prayer. Holy Communion about once a week I think. Then on Sunday. And - short service in the evening. Two shot services. Evensong and Complin. And then we - went out to - practice ourselves in different parishes. And -
 we taught in Sunday schools. They're enormous great - institutions. Hundreds and hundreds and hundreds of children.
\par I:\tab How did you find that?
\par WF:\tab Rather noisy rowdy things. Rather - these children, rather wild some of them. And then in the evenings we went
 out and preached sermon - to the long-suffering people. Sometimes children, sometimes - at a maternity home. Mm. Strange - strange place to send us to - I preached on the - Four Devils of the Apocalypse to them. Four - four dragons was it and - some drea
dful subject.
\par I:\tab Were you nervous at first?
\par WF:\tab Oh frightfully, yes, yes.
\par I:\tab Which was worse, the maternity home or the Sunday school?
\par WF:\tab Oh the Sunday school I think. And the maternity home - it wasn't so much trouble. Well the Sunday school was - it had a superintendent
\par I:\tab Did you have any free time to enjoy yourself there?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, we used to - play games on a bit of a - had a nice lawn and we used to - go and play cricket with the neighbouring teams. Dews - Dewsbury and - places round about Leeds. Schools and all places.
\par I:\tab Did you mix much with the people of the town or were you kept rather to yourselves?
\par WF:\tab Well - no, we mixed up with - we went visiting in our - in parishes which were assigned to us. Yes.
\par I:\tab So you were kind of student priests really?
\par WF:\tab Yes. It's a very good place - there was a lot going on there, a great city like Leeds. A very fine place, great pity they - dropped it 'cos it gave - us a lot of practical experience and to got to know these people.
\par I:\tab Were you surprised at all by what you found in Leeds? Poverty, or things that you hadn't expected?
\par WF:\tab Not particularly I don't think. Certain amount of out of work. Didn't seam to be desperate poverty in Leads. They were beginning to strike for higher wages. Which were about this thi
rty shillings a week then, but then - the value was different wasn't it.
\par I:\tab Did you feel at any time that you'd done the wrong thing, that you weren't in the right job?
\par WF:\tab Oh goodness, had awful worries. I was miserable at first, yes. Mm.
\par I:\tab Because you thought you couldn't do it?
\par WF:\tab Yes, terrified. Yes, I was miserable at first.
\par I:\tab Were the others miserable too?
\par WF:\tab I don't know. Seemed fairly quite happy.
\par I:\tab Did you make friends with people there?
\par WF:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab There weren't many of you were there?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes, I met some of them. I met one of them, and awfully liked - two of them. Then - dropped them now I think though. They may be dead for all I know, some of them.
\par I:\tab What was your standard of living like there?
\par WF:\tab No, it was quite a nice standard of living. Yes.
\par I:\tab It was better than school was it?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, much better. Nicest - mealtimes were on Fridays. Because we had a fast day then and - used to make - nice cakes, to make up for our - supposed austerities. And we - had fish, which I thought was so much nicer than meat.
\par I:\tab You don't like meat?
\par WF:\tab I don't, I never have now. It don't have any animal food at all now. And I feel better without it.
\par I:\tab Did you have exams to pass at the end of this period of training?
\par WF:\tab Oh dear, I don't remember exams at that place. I don't think we did.
\par I:\tab Did it get easier as you got into it, you began to forget your worries did you?
\par WF:\tab Yes, after a while. Took a long time.
\par I:\tab Were you homesick?
\par WF:\tab When - I was awfully homesick at school.
\par I:\tab At Leeds were you homesick?
\par WF:\tab Oh no. No.
\par I:\tab Because you'd been away at university?
\par WF:\tab Not homesick then.
\par I:\tab Was your father interested in what you were doing there?
\par WF:\tab Oh yes, yes, of course he was, yes.
\par I:\tab He kept an eye on you did he?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you get home to visit much?
\par WF:\tab Yes, I got - got home - in the holidays. In my first parish I was a vicar - accused me bitterly of having seven week's holiday - in the year, but -
\par I:\tab Was your first real parish?
\par WF:\tab Yes, that was first - I was assistant at - my brother came back from Canada then and - I wanted to see him. And - spent a good deal of time - together. He thought I was very much pampered.
\par I:\tab Spoilt?
\par WF:\tab Yes. Yes.
